<TEXT>
the week in music here has been busy the mostly 
mozart festival kicked off in lincoln center to run until aug 26 
willie nelson inaugurated a large new outdoor concert series on a 
hudson river pier 
and among the top musical delights was friday nights recreation 
of a may 2 1912 clef club concert when james reese europe brought 
125 black singers and instrumentalists to carnegie hall they 
performed music mostly by black composers mostly highquality 
highspirited light classical no spirituals it was a first for an 
american stage 
high points of the evening included jester hairston born in 
1901 vigorously conducting swing along for choir and orchestra 
and rain song for choir and orchestra both by will marion cook 
swing along got so much applause in 1912 it was performed again 
the same thing happened on friday 
another high point was two numbers by the versatile entertainers 
quartet piano two banjos and snare drum conductor maurice peress 
who organized the program couldnt find the quartets music from 
the 1912 concert he knew they were postragtime and prejazz but 
didnt know what they sounded like but he turned up a 1916 
recording and the quicktempo winter nights and down home 
rag on it were recreated friday starting with a delightfully 
trembling piano by frank owens 
the morgan state university male choir and boys choir of harlem 
sang europes clef club march benedictus from the mass in g 
by charles bolin and s coleridge taylors by the waters of 
babylon 
the diva engaged to sing swanee river in 1912 substituted 
my heart at thy sweet voice from the opera samson and 
delilah and barbara conrad did the same on friday 
william warfield sang j rosamond johnsons folksounding lil 
gal and he and miss conrad had fun dueting play that barber shop 
chord leon bates played a piano solo with flourishes dance 
heroique 
at a preconcert lecture dr reid badger talked about europe 
who formed the clef club as a booking agency for black musicians he 
maintained a clef club orchestra with mandolins and banjos instead 
of second violins for a strumming accompaniment really the 
beginning of orchestral jazz 
europe and his musicians often accompanied dancers vernon and 
irene castle the last piece on the program was a waltz he composed 
for them europe wrote for broadway and in the army in world war i 
he organized a brass band he isnt better known badger said 
because he died at 38 stabbed by a deranged musician during a 
concert in boston 
</TEXT>
