<TEXT>
an organization investigated by the fbi during 
its protests of us policies in central america says a senate 
intelligence committee report criticizing the fbi probe didnt go 
far enough 
hugh byrne political director of the committee in solidarity 
with the people of el salvador praised the senate for calling the 
fbi surveillance of his organization unjustified and telling the 
agency to purge its files of the case 
but we take strong issue with its conclusion that the fbi 
investigation was an aberration and that it wasnt politically 
motivated byrne said friday after the intelligence committee 
issued a report criticizing the fbis investigation of cispes 
between 1983 and 1985 
the report sharply criticized fbi management for letting the 
investigation continue and said the probe was based on allegations 
that should not have been considered credible 
the cispes files contain information about domestic political 
activities that the fbi should never have gathered said sen 
david boren dokla intelligence committee chairman and sen 
william cohen rmaine vice chairman 
that information must be removed from fbi records so it cannot 
be used to damage the reputation of innocent persons they said 
but the report called the investigation an aberration and 
said it did not reflect significant fbi political or ideological 
bias a point noted by both cispes and the fbi 
we dont believe that an investigation that involved 59 field 
officers and 178 spinoff investigations that resulted in retrievable 
information being held in fbi files about approximately 2375 
individuals and 1330 groups can be called an aberration said 
byrne 
we believe the investigation was politically motivated from the 
start said byrne 
the fbi said director william sessions is still reviewing the 
report but issued a statement saying it was significant that the 
report found the cispes investigation was not politically 
motivated to harass or influence legitimate first amendment 
activities 
an fbi spokesman said the files would not be immediately purged 
because there is continuing litigation over the investigation 
the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador was 
formed in 1980 because of reagan administration aid to el salvador 
which has totaled 3 billion since 1981 
a 1983 fbi memorandum is quoted in the report as attacking cispes 
for its protests and its practice of hosting salvadoran refugees who 
said their lives had been threatened by death squads in their 
homelands 
it is imperative at this time to formulate some plan of attack 
against cispes and specifically against individuals who 
defiantly display their contempt for the us government by making 
speeches and propagandizing their cause while asking for political 
asylum the memo said 
the report said there may not have been tangible harm intended 
or done to any groups or individuals involved in constitutionally 
protected activity but unjustified investigations of political 
expression and dissent can have a debilitating effect upon our 
political system 
despite such comments the center for constitutional rights 
which filed a lawsuit on behalf of cispes said critical and 
unresolved issues relating to the monitoring of first 
amendmentprotected activities of domestic groups that oppose us 
policy remain 
the probe was done while william webster now director of the 
cia was head of the fbi 
sessions has taken several internal measures over the probe 
including disciplining six employees at the supervisor unit chief 
and section chief levels 
