<TEXT>
a federal court ruling could make oil companies 
pay more to clean up oil spills including the massive spill from an 
exxon tanker that polluted the coastline of alaska says a 
congressman involved in the fight over liability for environmental 
accidents 
a threejudge panel of the us court of appeals for the district 
of columbia unanimously ruled friday the interior department should 
rewrite its rules on paying for oil spills to include the costs of 
more than just the monetary value of animals killed 
the decision raises chances that companies will have to pay the 
whole cost of restoring an environment said rep robert 
torricelli dnj 
torricelli said the case could have a major impact on damage 
payments by oil companies involved in spills such as the march 24 
accident that occurred when the tanker exxon valdez dumped 11 
million gallons of crude oil into alaskas pristine prince william 
sound 
this will make exxons exposure much greater said torricelli 
interior department spokesman al levitt said the agency hadnt 
studied the ruling and wouldnt have any comment he said no 
decision had been made on whether to appeal the case 
the regulations were issued three years ago to implement the 1977 
clean water act and the 1980 superfund law which required the 
government to write regulations determining the monetary costs of 
oil spills 
several environmental groups and states sued over the regulations 
under the 1986 regulations the interior department created a 
computer model putting a dollar value for lost use of various 
types of wildlife 
for example the cost of a fur seal was set at 15 based on the 
expected value of a seal pelt the cost of geese ranged up to 35 
based on their popularity among hunters 
but the appeals court said congress in writing the laws had 
intended that repayment should be more broadly drawn to consider not 
simply the value of lost wildlife but the larger cost of restoring 
the damaged environment 
because in some probably a majority of cases lostuse 
value will be lower than the cost of restoration interiors rule 
will result in damages awards too small to pay for the costs or 
restoration the ruling said 
the interior department has not yet decided on a damage 
assessment for either the alaskan spill or three smaller spills 
which occurred last month off the coasts of rhode island delaware 
and texas 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

