<TEXT>
a 45minute chat between nelson 
mandela and president pw botha has thrown government and 
antiapartheid forces off balance as they try to adjust their 
policies to the unprecedented event 
the meeting july 5 between the imprisoned african national 
congress leader and the retiring president caused confusion on all 
sides 
the exiled anc described the meeting as a publicity stunt but as 
praise poured in from other antiapartheid groups it withheld 
further comment 
it may be that the 73yearold botha facing forced retirement at 
the hands of the national party he controlled for 10 years gave 
history a push just to spite his designated successor 
the heir apparent fw de klerk has not commented on the 
meeting in cape town and the government seems to be scrambling to 
explain it without losing too many votes to the white rightwing in 
september parliamentary elections 
apparently preparing the groundwork for mandelas release the 
government is transforming its portrayal of him from a violent 
revolutionary to a statesman worthy of negotiating with the nations 
white leaders 
ambiguity extends even to mandela who turns 71 on july 18 and is 
serving a life term for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the 
government he insists he has not changed his views during 27 years 
in prison he has not met the governments demand for an outright 
renunciation of violence and he continues to call for the removal 
of a ban on the exiled anc 
but mandela in a statement released by prison services a week 
after he met botha said i only would like to contribute to the 
creation of the climate which would promote peace in south africa 
the policy of the anc and most sympathetic antiapartheid groups 
has been that no negotiations with the government are possible until 
mandela is freed yet the meeting and mandelas statement can be 
interpreted as indicating mandela has already begun a form of 
negotiation 
justice minister kobie coetsee who arranged and attended the 
meeting at bothas official residence first described it as a 
courtesy visit a week later he declared it a breakthrough 
foreign minister pik botha mindful of the need to improve south 
africas image abroad called it an event of the utmost historic 
importance 
information minister stoffel van der merwe aware of the danger 
of startling white voters before the elections said the meeting was 
part of the broader process of preparing the groundwork for future 
negotiations 
only the extremeright proapartheid conservative party has made 
its position clear conservative party leader andries treurnicht 
attacked the government for talking to the anc and said its 
attempt to enhance mandelas status to that of a folk hero is 
transparent and will not work 
progovernment news media presented mandelas commitment to peace 
as a dramatic change but it is new in south africa only because 
mandelas views have been suppressed for so long 
mandelas words made headlines around the country and were read 
on governmentrun television and radio his picture which cannot be 
published legally has been printed in major newspapers whose 
editors believe they will not be prosecuted 
first reactions from mandelas wife winnie and from the rev 
frank chikane secretarygeneral of the south african council of 
churches suggested mandela may have been forced into the meeting or 
been unaware of its implications 
mrs mandela and chikane reversed course after mandelas 
statement saying the discussions were a positive development rather 
than a government ploy 
anc spokesman tom sebina said in lusaka zambia it would be 
wrong for anybody to believe that the meeting signified the start of 
negotiations between the black people of south africa and the 
national party government 
he did not react to mandelas statement but his comment 
contained an important shift he referred to the government 
instead of the apartheid regime 
mandela as a free man able to act as a politician rather than a 
symbol poses problems that the anc has not fully addressed 
although he is regarded as the anc leader the highest post 
mandela held before the organization was outlawed in 1960 was 
deputypresident general the anc has a president oliver tambo who 
has lived in exile for 29 years 
mandela had set guidelines for the ancs military wing calling 
for carefully considered attacks on government targets and arguing 
against acts that would cause indiscriminate deaths as the ancs 
bombing campaign has done 
the majority of mandelas supporters were born after he was 
jailed have never heard his words and have grown up in an 
environment of blackonblack township political strife that did not 
exist in 1962 
there has been built up around him such a folklore hero role 
that he would be recieved as a hero said helen suzman a white 
antiapartheid member of parliament but how does one know what 
hes going to suggest to them and what they are prepared to accept 
</TEXT>
