<TEXT>
the countrys largest black 
union said saturday it wants to form a huge antiapartheid coalition 
to coordinate strategies among opposition groups 
the national union of mineworkers said it will seek to arrange a 
conference no later than october to bring together the core forces 
of the mass democratic movement 
it is important to win over all antiapartheid forces to our 
side said the union which has about 300000 members 
antiapartheid groups have been urgently trying to formulate 
unified strategies since the july 5 meeting between president pw 
botha and jailed black nationalist nelson mandela leader of the 
african national congress 
opposition groups initially dismissed the talks as government 
propaganda that involved no shift in policy but several 
organizations revised their assessment and called it a positive 
development after mandela released a statement wednesday indicating 
he welcomed the chance to talk with botha 
the mineworkers union said the congress of south african trade 
unions the countrys largest labor federation and the united 
democratic front the largest antiapartheid coalition would play 
leading roles in the coalition it sought to establish 
however both groups are banned from participating in political 
activities 
the mineworkers did not explain how these organizations could 
become active in politics 
the outlawed anc and other antiapartheid groups have said there 
can be no negotiations with the government until it meets several 
basic demands such as freeing all political prisoners legalizing 
banned organizations and lifting the state of emergency 
the antiapartheid movement has found it increasingly difficult 
to organize under the 3yearold state of emergency during which 
more than 30 opposition groups have been banned 
mandela has been imprisoned since 1962 and is serving a life 
sentence for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the government 
his meeting with botha suggests the anc leader is willing to talk 
with the government though his demand for a nonracial democracy in 
south africa is unchanged 
the whiteled government also appears to have eased its policy of 
having no contact with the anc which it labels a terrorist 
organization 
under south africas apartheid policies the 28 million blacks 
have no voice in national affairs the 5 million whites control the 
government and economy while maintaining separate neighborhoods 
schools and health facilities 
