<TEXT>
while leaders of the worlds seven richest nations 
met behind closed doors saturday representatives of the seven 
poorest peoples held a public meeting across town on the left 
bank 
bangladesh burkina faso haiti mozambique the philippines 
zaire and the brazilian amazon were represented by doctors poets 
womens and human rights activists labor leaders and ethnic 
emissaries 
orlando melgueiros da silva barechested and in a feather 
headdress represented brazils union of indigenous nations 
the meeting of the seven poorest peoples occurred under the 
auspices of the other economic summit an annual conference 
searching for alternative solutions at the same time the leaders of 
the united states west germany japan france britain italy and 
canada are meeting 
we seek an alternative economic development which will do away 
with social injustice the norths domination of third world 
countries and the thoughtless pillage of the earths resources 
explained the conference paper 
more than 1000 participants attended the meeting 
a final declaration issued saturday night called for a radical 
transformation of the international political and economic system 
to make sure decisions were not taken just by the rich countries 
but with all the peoples of the world 
the statement also called for a ban on the use of international 
loans for arms purchases for controls on destructive energy 
consumption and forgiveness of the debt owed by poor countries to 
the rich 
the summit held alongside the sevennation economic summit or 
g7 every year since 1974 included such seminars as education 
for the third millenium and without arms citizens which 
explored the role of private citizens in the peace process and 
disarmament 
like the leaders across town the alternative summiteers also 
discussed international debt economics and the environment 
konrad von moltke a senior fellow with the conservation 
foundation and the world wide fund for nature in washington dc 
