<TEXT>
reseachers have successfully made the first test 
run of the worlds biggest atom smasher a 17mile circular tunnel 
designed to unlock secrets of how the universe took shape 
scientists said saturday 
on friday evening scientists at the european laboratory for 
particle physics outside the capital sent a first beam of particles 
around the new particle accelerator known as the large 
electronpositron collider or lep 
the 790 million machine built underground beneath the 
frenchswiss border is expected to put the european lab ahead of 
us rivals in the search for new discoveries in highenergy 
physics although plans are in the works for a 53mile super 
collider in texas 
carlo rubbia an italian physics professor and nobel laureate who 
heads the lab cheered along with other scientists in the control 
room as instruments showed a positron beam completed its course in 
50 minutes said lab spokesman neil calder said 
a positron is a positively charged antiparticle of an electron 
this simply means that all parts of the machine all the 
magnets are correctly positioned said the spokesman for the lab 
outside geneva known by the french acronym cern 
the collider built over eight years with funding from cerns 14 
member states is the most powerful particle accelerator and the 
largest scientific instrument ever made 
rubbia says it should guarantee europe a dominant position in 
particle physics for many years to come 
the lep will recreate with new sophistication the wild swirl of 
matter just after the socalled big bang the explosion many 
scientists believe created the universe up to 20 billion years ago 
the threemile stanford linear collider at menlo park calif in 
april won the race to produce the first socalled z particles which 
scientists say could have existed naturally for only an instant 
after a big bang 
but the cern machine is expected to produce thousands of z 
particles by september opening a greater scope for discovery 
watching z particles decay into other particles is expected to 
yield new clues to the structure of matter and the development of 
the universe 
rubbia shared the 1984 physics nobel prize with dutch scientist 
simon van der meer for discovering the z particle in an old particle 
accelerator at cern but stronger colliders are needed to make 
enough particles to allow scientists to draw conclusions 
z particles have also been produced at the fermi national 
accelerator laboratory near chicago that fourmile track was the 
biggest accelerator in the world until the new cern machine was 
built 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

